evaluation.response:
So you're having a tough time lately and have been feeling down about the past. It's understandable to look back and think about perceived mistakes, like pushing deals too hard or not being home enough. But try to be kind to yourself about those things. Everyone has regrets, right?

It's scary to feel like a burden and not want to burden your loved ones with your concerns. That's devastating when you're feeling like you're all alone in this.

It's understandable why the AI health coach's suggestions might feel validating. It can be tempting to hide your feelings and pretend everything's okay. But sometimes, hiding your feelings can sustain them. Isolating yourself can trap you in those painful feelings.

Try to talk to your kids. It might be a relief to connect with them and let them know what you're going through. Your burdens might not be as heavy if you share them with them. You could give them a say in the more emotional aspects of your decision-making.

If you're not comfortable with that (and that's totally okay, too), you could try to reach out to a mental health provider. Therapists have training and education to help you organize your thoughts and feelings, so you can work through this heavy time with more guidance.&#x20;

Just remember that you're not alone. There's no pride worth losing in speaking to the ones you love and letting them take some weight off your shoulders for a little. You will come out of this even stronger a person.&#x20;

There has been some fear that you've accepted this is an irreversible change. You've been identifying with this new definition of "old, slow, better off out of the way." Ever since giving up golf, you've started looking at daily life that way too - basically like you're done even pursuing daily life.&#x20;

**You Must Come Out of Hiding**

You may not want to keep living a life of fear of how your health was going to change for the worse. This fear of bad things has left you feeling stagnated in pursuing daily life. Ever since the fear started creeping in slowly, it's only multiplied. But you are your worst critic; you are hard on yourself and give up too quickly.&#x20;

If this is bad news, then the good news is that you can rewrite the narrative. This doesn't have to continue defining your life. You may need support reaching new daily successes, but you will get there.

**The Kindness of Small Wins**

Instead of focusing on the grind of a big goal (ex: "start playing golf again"), think about one small step in the right direction (for golf, walking without regular breaks). Focus on how far you will come. The last thing you want to do is trick yourself into thinking that you've given yourself an easy pass by creating this impressive comeback narrative and in reality still not doing anything.
